:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Botreaux was born about 1135, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, his father, William De Bottreaux, was 17 and his mother, Alice Corbet, was 37. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1209, in his hometown, at the age of 75, and was buried in Gloucestershire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1135–1209":"umbes 1135–1209","1135–1209":"1135–1209","1146–1220":"1146–1220","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1172–1220":"1172–1220","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1175–1199":"1175–1199","1119–1175":"1119–1175","1100–1149":"1100–1149","before 1149":"enne 1149","1220":"1220","1175":"1175","1173":"1173","1172":"1172","1170":"1170","1149":"1149","Abt 1135":"umbes 1135","1146":"1146","1135":"1135","1134":"1134","1100":"1100","1199":"1199","1209":"1209","1119":"1119","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"